Masters (MS) in New Zealand: Eligibility, Scope and Top Colleges for Indian Students

  • 844 Reads
  • 3 min Read
  • By:CANAM Group
  • Updated On:May 22,2023 03:54 PM IST

Masters in New Zealand is renowned globally for its diverse specializations, industry-oriented degrees, affordability, scholarships, quality programs and cultural diversity. Masters in New Zealand offers exceptional research opportunities through its government-aided Crown Research Institutes. The experienced team at Canam Consultants offers comprehensive information and assistance to aspirants who desire to study in New Zealand.

New Zealand is rapidly becoming a popular study destination for international students pursuing Masters courses and research degrees. Masters in New Zealand typically lasts two years and combines theoretical knowledge with practical field experience. Masters in New Zealand focuses on equipping students with the skills necessary to secure positions at global brands. New Zealand's globally recognized universities and highly ranked education systems enable international students to pursue lucrative careers after their studies. Two intake cycles are offered for the masters program to study in New Zealand (July and February). New Zealand is home to seven government-aided Crown Research Institutes (CRI) that offer exceptional research opportunities to masters and PhD students.

Reasons to Study Masters in New Zealand:

1.Diverse Specializations: Choosing to study in New Zealand offer various MS specializations, including artificial intelligence, machine learning, engineering, data science, network, web development, data management, and spatial information technology.

2.Industry-oriented Degrees: Masters in New Zealand is highly work-oriented, meaning students get practical skills and knowledge to apply in the workplace. It also increases the chances of finding employment after graduation.

3.Affordable: Compared to the other top study destinations, pursuing a masters in New Zealand is affordable for international students

4.Scholarships and Funding: Several scholarships, grants, and funding options are available for international students to study in New Zealand.

5.Quality Programs: Eight major academic institutions in New Zealand have been recognized by the QS World University Rankings 2021 for their teaching excellence and quality programs.

6.Safe and Secure: New Zealand is the second-safest country in the world, according to the Global Peace Index, 2021. This means that university campuses are safe and secure for students.

7.Culturally Diverse: New Zealand is a culturally diversified country, with a rich cultural heritage integrated into the education system. International students are warmly welcomed, and they can easily integrate into the culture.

8.Permanent Residency Opportunities: Students with a job offer and the ability to prove their intent to stay in the country can apply for permanent residency in New Zealand.

9.Student Discounts: New Zealand offers a popular student card that gives scholars access to offers and discounts across food, clothes, travel, entertainment, and airfares.

Masters in New Zealand: Eligibility and Requirements

While the eligibility and requirements for a Masters in New Zealand differs for colleges and universities some standard requirements and eligibility criteria study in New Zealand are:

Requirements to Study Masters in New Zealand:

1.Academic Qualifications: Applicants must hold a relevant undergraduate or equivalent qualification from a recognized institution.

2.Language Proficiency: To study in New Zealand, students whose native language is not English must prove their English proficiency by taking a standardized test like IELTS, TOEFL or PTE.

3.Letters of Recommendation: Some universities in New Zealand require applicants to provide letters of recommendation (LOR) as a reference to their performance from professors or previous employer.

4.Personal Statement: Students are also required to submit a personal statement outlining their academic achievements, professional experience, and future goals to study Masters in New Zealand.

5.Application Fees: Students also need to pay a non-refundable application fee when submitting their application.

6.Visa Requirements: International students must obtain a student visa to study in New Zealand, which requires them to meet specific requirements and provide supporting documentation.

Eligibility to Study Masters in New Zealand:

1.Academic Eligibility: To apply for a masters degree in New Zealand, students must acquire relevant undergraduate or equivalent qualification from a recognized institution.

2.Language Eligibility: Students must prove their English language proficiency through language tests like IELTS, TOEFL and PTE.

3.Work Experience: While work experience is not mandatory requirement for admission to a program in New Zealand, it may be beneficial in some cases.

4.Age: International students must be at least 18 years of old at the time of applying for the course.

5.Visa Eligibility: International students must meet the visa requirements to study in New Zealand, which includes financial eligibility, health and character requirements, and genuine intentions to study in the country.

Visa Requirements to Study Masters in New Zealand

Students must fulfil the following requirements to study in New Zealand:

  • In order to apply for a student visa in New Zealand, students must have an offer letter from a university or college approved by the New Zealand Qualifications Authority (NZQA)
  • Students must provide evidence of funds sufficient to cover their living expenses during their stay in New Zealand, including expenses related to tuition fees, accommodation costs, and other living expenses

  • Students must provide a medical certificate and a police verification certificate to qualify the health and character requirements to study masters in New Zealand
  • Students must also have a comprehensive medical insurance for their stay in New Zealand.

Types of Masters Degrees Offered in New Zealand:

The table below presents the different types of masters degrees offered in New Zealand:

Types of Masters Degrees
Courses Description
Traditional Masters Programmes
These programs are perfect for students looking to enhancing their academic knowledge in a specific field. These are designed to build on the foundational knowledge acquired in the undergraduate degree and typically offer qualifications such as a Masters of Arts (MA) or Master of Science (M.Sc.) to study in New Zealand.
Change of Direction Masters Degree
Programs under this degree provide a comprehensive foundation in the subject before offering students the opportunity to specialize in a specific aspect. Students get the advantage of the flexibility and adaptability that comes with advanced education and successfully focus on their career.
Graduate Entry Professional Qualifications
These programs provide students with the necessary knowledge and expertise to qualify for professional careers. This can help students stand out in a competitive job market and make a meaningful impact in their chosen field.
Professional Development Qualifications
Professional Development Qualifications in New Zealand are great option for students with relevant work experience, wishing to enhance or modify their career path. Unlike graduate-entry courses, these programs are designed for candidates with experience in their chosen field.

Application Deadlines for the Masters in New Zealand:

The application deadlines for the masters degree in New Zealand may differ for different universities and colleges.
There are two prominent intakes for masters in New Zealand:

January/February Intake
July Intake

Students who apply for the January/February Intake to study for masters in New Zealand should apply by October 31st of the previous year.
Students who apply for the July Intake to study for masters in New Zealand should apply by 30th April of the same year.
For more information, you can also visit Intakes in New Zealand

FAQ

Which are the two major intakes to study masters in New Zealand?

The January/February Intake and July Intake are the two major intakes to study masters in New Zealand.

Can a student choose a different subject of study for masters in New Zealand?

Yes, under the Change of Direction Masters Degree, students can opt for different subjects that they have not studied earlier.

What is the length of the masters course in New Zealand?

Masters in New Zealand typically lasts two years and combines theoretical knowledge with practical field experience.

Is the GRE score compulsory to study MS in New Zealand?

Submitting GRE scores in New Zealand is not very popular, as most universities in New Zealand give more importance to your GPA.

Is New Zealand suitable for masters?

Masters in New Zealand focuses on equipping students with the skills necessary to secure positions at global brands. So, yes, New Zealand is a great place to study masters.

Are postgraduate diplomas and masters considered the same in New Zealand?

No, in New Zealand, a postgraduate diploma is not equivalent to a masters degree as it is a shorter course without the same level of subject specialization.
